{"metadata":{"title":"Getting started","role":"article","modules":[{"name":"ComposableArchitecture"}],"roleHeading":"Article"},"sections":[],"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Adding-the-Composable-Architecture-as-a-dependency","text":"Adding the Composable Architecture as a dependency"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To use the Composable Architecture in a SwiftPM project, add it to the dependencies of your"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"Package.swift and specify the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"ComposableArchitecture"},{"text":" product in any targets that need access to","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"the library:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"swift","code":["let package = Package(","  dependencies: [","    .package(","      url: \"https:\/\/github.com\/pointfreeco\/swift-composable-architecture\",","      from: \"1.0.0\"","    ),","  ],","  targets: [","    .target(","      name: \"<target-name>\",","      dependencies: [","        .product(","          name: \"ComposableArchitecture\",","          package: \"swift-composable-architecture\"","        )","      ]","    )","  ]",")"],"type":"codeListing"},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Writing-your-first-feature","text":"Writing your first feature"},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For a step-by-step interactive tutorial, be sure to check out"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/tutorials\/MeetComposableArchitecture","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"."}]}],"style":"note","type":"aside","name":"Note"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To build a feature using the Composable Architecture you define some types and values that model"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"your domain:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"State"}]},{"type":"text","text":": A type that describes the data your feature needs to perform its logic and render its"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"UI.","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Action"}],"type":"strong"},{"text":": A type that represents all of the actions that can happen in your feature, such as","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"user actions, notifications, event sources and more."}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Reducer"}],"type":"strong"},{"text":": A function that describes how to evolve the current state of the app to the next","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"state given an action. The reducer is also responsible for returning any effects that should be","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"run, such as API requests, which can be done by returning an ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Effect"},{"text":" value.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Store"}],"type":"strong"},{"text":": The runtime that actually drives your feature. You send all user actions to the store","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"so that the store can run the reducer and effects, and you can observe state changes in the","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"store so that you can update UI.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The benefits of doing this are that you will instantly unlock testability of your feature, and you"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"will be able to break large, complex features into smaller domains that can be glued together.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"As a basic example, consider a UI that shows a number along with “+” and “−” buttons that increment"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"and decrement the number. To make things interesting, suppose there is also a button that when","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"tapped makes an API request to fetch a random fact about that number and displays it in the view.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To implement this feature we create a new type that will house the domain and behavior of the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"feature, and it will be annotated with the ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/Reducer()","isActive":true,"overridingTitle":"@Reducer","overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"@Reducer"}],"type":"reference"},{"text":" macro:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["import ComposableArchitecture","","@Reducer","struct Feature {","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"In here we need to define a type for the feature’s state, which consists of an integer for the","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"current count, as well as an optional string that represents the fact being presented:"}]},{"code":["@Reducer","struct Feature {","  @ObservableState","  struct State: Equatable {","    var count = 0","    var numberFact: String?","  }","}"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"style":"note","name":"Note","type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"We’ve applied the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"@ObservableState"},{"type":"text","text":" macro to "},{"code":"State","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" in order to take advantage of the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"observation tools in the library."}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We also need to define a type for the feature’s actions. There are the obvious actions, such as"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"tapping the decrement button, increment button, or fact button. But there are also some slightly","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"non-obvious ones, such as the action that occurs when we receive a response from the fact API","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"request:"}]},{"syntax":"swift","code":["@Reducer","struct Feature {","  @ObservableState","  struct State: Equatable { \/* ... *\/ }","  enum Action {","    case decrementButtonTapped","    case incrementButtonTapped","    case numberFactButtonTapped","    case numberFactResponse(String)","  }","}"],"type":"codeListing"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"And then we implement the "},{"code":"body","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" property, which is responsible for composing the actual logic and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"behavior for the feature. In it we can use the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Reduce"},{"text":" reducer to describe how to change the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"current state to the next state, and what effects need to be executed. Some actions don’t need to"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"execute effects, and they can return ","type":"text"},{"code":".none","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" to represent that:"}]},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["@Reducer","struct Feature {","  @ObservableState","  struct State: Equatable { \/* ... *\/ }","  enum Action { \/* ... *\/ }","","  var body: some Reducer<State, Action> {","    Reduce { state, action in","      switch action {","      case .decrementButtonTapped:","        state.count -= 1","        return .none","","      case .incrementButtonTapped:","        state.count += 1","        return .none","","      case .numberFactButtonTapped:","        return .run { [count = state.count] send in","          let (data, _) = try await URLSession.shared.data(","            from: URL(string: \"http:\/\/numbersapi.com\/\\(count)\/trivia\")!","          )","          await send(","            .numberFactResponse(String(decoding: data, as: UTF8.self))","          )","        }","","      case let .numberFactResponse(fact):","        state.numberFact = fact","        return .none","      }","    }","  }","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"And then finally we define the view that displays the feature. It holds onto a "},{"code":"StoreOf<Feature>","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":"","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"so that it can observe all changes to the state and re-render, and we can send all user actions to","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"the store so that state changes:"}]},{"code":["struct FeatureView: View {","  let store: StoreOf<Feature>","","  var body: some View {","    Form {","      Section {","        Text(\"\\(store.count)\")","        Button(\"Decrement\") { store.send(.decrementButtonTapped) }","        Button(\"Increment\") { store.send(.incrementButtonTapped) }","      }","","      Section {","        Button(\"Number fact\") { store.send(.numberFactButtonTapped) }","      }","      ","      if let fact = store.numberFact {","        Text(fact)","      }","    }","  }","}"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"It is also straightforward to have a UIKit controller driven off of this store. You can observe","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"state changes in the store in ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"viewDidLoad"},{"type":"text","text":", and then populate the UI components with data from"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"the store. The code is a bit longer than the SwiftUI version, so we have collapsed it here:","type":"text"}]},{"code":["class FeatureViewController: UIViewController {","  let store: StoreOf<Feature>","","  init(store: StoreOf<Feature>) {","    self.store = store","    super.init(nibName: nil, bundle: nil)","  }","","  required init?(coder: NSCoder) {","    fatalError(\"init(coder:) has not been implemented\")","  }","","  override func viewDidLoad() {","    super.viewDidLoad()","","    let countLabel = UILabel()","    let decrementButton = UIButton()","    let incrementButton = UIButton()","    let factLabel = UILabel()","    ","    \/\/ Omitted: Add subviews and set up constraints...","    ","    observe { [weak self] in","      guard let self ","      else { return }","      ","      countLabel.text = \"\\(self.store.text)\"","      factLabel.text = self.store.numberFact","    }","  }","","  @objc private func incrementButtonTapped() {","    self.store.send(.incrementButtonTapped)","  }","  @objc private func decrementButtonTapped() {","    self.store.send(.decrementButtonTapped)","  }","  @objc private func factButtonTapped() {","    self.store.send(.numberFactButtonTapped)","  }","}"],"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Once we are ready to display this view, for example in the app’s entry point, we can construct a"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"store. This can be done by specifying the initial state to start the application in, as well as"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"the reducer that will power the application:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["import ComposableArchitecture","","@main","struct MyApp: App {","  var body: some Scene {","    WindowGroup {","      FeatureView(","        store: Store(initialState: Feature.State()) {","          Feature()","        }","      )","    }","  }","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"And that is enough to get something on the screen to play around with. It’s definitely a few more"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"steps than if you were to do this in a vanilla SwiftUI way, but there are a few benefits. It gives"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"us a consistent manner to apply state mutations, instead of scattering logic in some observable"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"objects and in various action closures of UI components. It also gives us a concise way of"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"expressing side effects. And we can immediately test this logic, including the effects, without"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"doing much additional work."}]},{"text":"Testing your feature","type":"heading","anchor":"Testing-your-feature","level":2},{"type":"aside","style":"note","name":"Note","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For more in-depth information on testing, see the dedicated "},{"text":"doc:Testing","type":"text"},{"text":"","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"article."}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To test use a "},{"code":"TestStore","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", which can be created with the same information as the "},{"code":"Store","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", but it"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"does extra work to allow you to assert how your feature evolves as actions are sent:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["@Test","func basics() async {","  let store = TestStore(initialState: Feature.State()) {","    Feature()","  }","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Once the test store is created we can use it to make an assertion of an entire user flow of steps.","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"Each step of the way we need to prove that state changed how we expect. For example, we can","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"simulate the user flow of tapping on the increment and decrement buttons:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["\/\/ Test that tapping on the increment\/decrement buttons changes the count","await store.send(.incrementButtonTapped) {","  $0.count = 1","}","await store.send(.decrementButtonTapped) {","  $0.count = 0","}"]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Further, if a step causes an effect to be executed, which feeds data back into the store, we must"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"assert on that. For example, if we simulate the user tapping on the fact button we expect to"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"receive a fact response back with the fact, which then causes the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"numberFact"},{"type":"text","text":" state to be"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"populated:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["await store.send(.numberFactButtonTapped)","","await store.receive(\\.numberFactResponse) {","  $0.numberFact = ???","}"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"However, how do we know what fact is going to be sent back to us?","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Currently our reducer is using an effect that reaches out into the real world to hit an API server,"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"and that means we have no way to control its behavior. We are at the whims of our internet"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"connectivity and the availability of the API server in order to write this test."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"It would be better for this dependency to be passed to the reducer so that we can use a live"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"dependency when running the application on a device, but use a mocked dependency for tests. We can"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"do this by adding a property to the ","type":"text"},{"code":"Feature","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" reducer:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"swift","code":["@Reducer","struct Feature {","  let numberFact: (Int) async throws -> String","  \/\/ ...","}"],"type":"codeListing"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Then we can use it in the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"reduce"},{"type":"text","text":" implementation:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"swift","code":["case .numberFactButtonTapped:","  return .run { [count = state.count] send in ","    let fact = try await self.numberFact(count)","    await send(.numberFactResponse(fact))","  }"],"type":"codeListing"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"And in the entry point of the application we can provide a version of the dependency that actually"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"interacts with the real world API server:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["@main","struct MyApp: App {","  var body: some Scene {","    WindowGroup {","      FeatureView(","        store: Store(initialState: Feature.State()) {","          Feature(","            numberFact: { number in","              let (data, _) = try await URLSession.shared.data(","                from: URL(string: \"http:\/\/numbersapi.com\/\\(number)\")!","              )","              return String(decoding: data, as: UTF8.self)","            }","          )","        }","      )","    }","  }","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"But in tests we can use a mock dependency that immediately returns a deterministic, predictable","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"fact:","type":"text"}]},{"code":["@Test","func basics() async {","  let store = TestStore(initialState: Feature.State()) {","    Feature(numberFact: { \"\\($0) is a good number Brent\" })","  }","}"],"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"With that little bit of upfront work we can finish the test by simulating the user tapping on the","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"fact button, and then receiving the response from the dependency to present the fact:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["await store.send(.numberFactButtonTapped)","","await store.receive(\\.numberFactResponse) {","  $0.numberFact = \"0 is a good number Brent\"","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We can also improve the ergonomics of using the "},{"code":"numberFact","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" dependency in our application. Over"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"time the application may evolve into many features, and some of those features may also want access","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"to "},{"code":"numberFact","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", and explicitly passing it through all layers can get annoying. There is a process"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"you can follow to “register” dependencies with the library, making them instantly available to any","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"layer in the application."}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"For more in-depth information on dependency management, see the dedicated","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/DependencyManagement","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" article."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"style":"note","name":"Note","type":"aside"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"We can start by wrapping the number fact functionality in a new type:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"swift","code":["struct NumberFactClient {","  var fetch: (Int) async throws -> String","}"],"type":"codeListing"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"And then registering that type with the dependency management system by conforming the client to"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"the "},{"code":"DependencyKey","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" protocol, which requires you to specify the live value to use when running the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"application in simulators or devices:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["extension NumberFactClient: DependencyKey {","  static let liveValue = Self(","    fetch: { number in","      let (data, _) = try await URLSession.shared","        .data(from: URL(string: \"http:\/\/numbersapi.com\/\\(number)\")!","      )","      return String(decoding: data, as: UTF8.self)","    }","  )","}","","extension DependencyValues {","  var numberFact: NumberFactClient {","    get { self[NumberFactClient.self] }","    set { self[NumberFactClient.self] = newValue }","  }","}"]},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"With that little bit of upfront work done you can instantly start making use of the dependency in","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"any feature by using the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"@Dependency"},{"type":"text","text":" property wrapper:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"diff","code":[" @Reducer"," struct Feature {","-  let numberFact: (Int) async throws -> String","+  @Dependency(\\.numberFact) var numberFact","   ","   …","","-  try await self.numberFact(count)","+  try await self.numberFact.fetch(count)"," }"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This code works exactly as it did before, but you no longer have to explicitly pass the dependency","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"when constructing the feature’s reducer. When running the app in previews, the simulator or on a","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"device, the live dependency will be provided to the reducer, and in tests the test dependency will"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"be provided.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This means the entry point to the application no longer needs to construct dependencies:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","code":["@main","struct MyApp: App {","  var body: some Scene {","    WindowGroup {","      FeatureView(","        store: Store(initialState: Feature.State()) {","          Feature()","        }","      )","    }","  }","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"And the test store can be constructed without specifying any dependencies, but you can still"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"override any dependency you need to for the purpose of the test:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["let store = TestStore(initialState: Feature.State()) {","  Feature()","} withDependencies: {","  $0.numberFact.fetch = { \"\\($0) is a good number Brent\" }","}","","\/\/ ..."]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"That is the basics of building and testing a feature in the Composable Architecture. There are"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"a lot"}]},{"text":" more things to be explored. Be sure to check out the ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/tutorials\/MeetComposableArchitecture","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":""},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"tutorial, as well as dedicated articles on ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/DependencyManagement","isActive":true},{"text":", ","type":"text"},{"text":"doc:Testing","type":"text"},{"text":",","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/Navigation","type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/Performance","isActive":true},{"text":", and more. Also, the ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/pointfreeco\/swift-composable-architecture\/tree\/main\/Examples","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" directory has"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"a bunch of projects to explore to see more advanced usages."}],"type":"paragraph"}]}],"kind":"article","hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture"]]},"schemaVersion":{"minor":3,"patch":0,"major":0},"seeAlsoSections":[{"anchor":"Essentials","generated":true,"title":"Essentials","identifiers":["doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/DependencyManagement","doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/Navigation","doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/SharingState","doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/Performance","doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/FAQ"]}],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/GettingStarted","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"abstract":[{"text":"Learn how to integrate the Composable Architecture into your project and write your first","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"application."}],"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/composablearchitecture\/gettingstarted"]}],"references":{"doc://ComposableArchitecture/documentation/ComposableArchitecture/Navigation":{"abstract":[{"text":"Learn how to use the navigation tools in the library, including how to best model your domains, how","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"to integrate features in the reducer and view layers, and how to write tests."}],"kind":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/Navigation","role":"collectionGroup","title":"Navigation","url":"\/documentation\/composablearchitecture\/navigation","type":"topic"},"doc://ComposableArchitecture/documentation/ComposableArchitecture/DependencyManagement":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/DependencyManagement","title":"Dependencies","type":"topic","kind":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Learn how to register dependencies with the library so that they can be immediately accessible from"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"any reducer."}],"url":"\/documentation\/composablearchitecture\/dependencymanagement","role":"article"},"doc://ComposableArchitecture/documentation/ComposableArchitecture":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture","type":"topic","kind":"symbol","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"The Composable Architecture (TCA, for short) is a library for building applications in a consistent"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"and understandable way, with composition, testing, and ergonomics in mind. It can be used in","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"SwiftUI, UIKit, and more, and on any Apple platform (iOS, macOS, tvOS, and watchOS)."}],"url":"\/documentation\/composablearchitecture","title":"ComposableArchitecture","role":"collection"},"doc://ComposableArchitecture/documentation/ComposableArchitecture/Reducer":{"role":"symbol","kind":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/composablearchitecture\/reducer","title":"Reducer","identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/Reducer","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"A protocol that describes how to evolve the current state of an application to the next state,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"given an action, and describes what "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/Effect","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"s should be executed later by the store, if any."}],"navigatorTitle":[{"text":"Reducer","kind":"identifier"}],"type":"topic","fragments":[{"text":"protocol","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"Reducer","kind":"identifier"}]},"doc://ComposableArchitecture/documentation/ComposableArchitecture/Reducer()":{"url":"\/documentation\/composablearchitecture\/reducer()","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Helps implement the conformance to the "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/Reducer","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" protocol for a type."}],"type":"topic","title":"Reducer()","fragments":[{"text":"macro","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"Reducer","kind":"identifier"},{"kind":"text","text":"()"}],"kind":"symbol","identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/Reducer()","role":"symbol"},"https://github.com/pointfreeco/swift-composable-architecture/tree/main/Examples":{"type":"link","titleInlineContent":[{"text":"Examples","type":"text"}],"title":"Examples","url":"https:\/\/github.com\/pointfreeco\/swift-composable-architecture\/tree\/main\/Examples","identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/pointfreeco\/swift-composable-architecture\/tree\/main\/Examples"},"doc://ComposableArchitecture/documentation/ComposableArchitecture/FAQ":{"url":"\/documentation\/composablearchitecture\/faq","type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/FAQ","title":"Frequently asked questions","role":"article","kind":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"A collection of some of the most common questions and comments people have concerning the library."}]},"doc://ComposableArchitecture/tutorials/MeetComposableArchitecture":{"url":"\/tutorials\/meetcomposablearchitecture","type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/tutorials\/MeetComposableArchitecture","title":"Meet the Composable Architecture","role":"overview","kind":"overview","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"The Composable Architecture (TCA, for short) is a library for building applications in a"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"consistent and understandable way, with composition, testing, and ergonomics in mind. It can be"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"used in SwiftUI, UIKit, and more, and on any Apple platform (iOS, macOS, tvOS, and watchOS)."}]},"doc://ComposableArchitecture/documentation/ComposableArchitecture/Performance":{"url":"\/documentation\/composablearchitecture\/performance","abstract":[{"text":"Learn how to improve the performance of features built in the Composable Architecture.","type":"text"}],"type":"topic","title":"Performance","kind":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/Performance","role":"article"},"doc://ComposableArchitecture/documentation/ComposableArchitecture/SharingState":{"title":"Sharing state","type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/ComposableArchitecture\/documentation\/ComposableArchitecture\/SharingState","abstract":[{"text":"Learn techniques for sharing state throughout many parts of your application, and how to persist","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"data to user defaults, the file system, and other external mediums.","type":"text"}],"kind":"article","url":"\/documentation\/composablearchitecture\/sharingstate","role":"collectionGroup"}}}